      "rationale": "FEA-predicted construct stiffness agreed with experimental mean within 8.4% across all three FEA implementations. Predicted yield load was within 11.2% of experimental mean. Prediction intervals computed via Monte Carlo uncertainty propagation overlapped the experimental distribution for all 11 specimens."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield load) are directly linked to the clinical performance question and regulatory acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and yield load under compression-bending are the primary mechanical performance metrics used in ASTM F1717 regulatory submissions. These QoIs are directly relevant to the risk of implant mechanical failure in the clinical use environment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities replicate the loading mode, geometry, and material class of the intended use.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the ASTM F1717 compression-bending protocol applied to a non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct, which is the same device class and loading mode addressed in the model's intended application. Validation is therefore highly relevant to the use context implicit in this assessment."
